1
00:00:00,040 --> 00:00:02,580
Virtual threads were introduced in Java 21

2
00:00:02,580 --> 00:00:04,800
So what problems do virtual threads actually solve?

3
00:00:04,800 --> 00:00:06,200
In what scenarios can it be used

4
00:00:06,200 --> 00:00:08,620
What are the differences between virtual threads and Go's goroutines?

5
00:00:08,620 --> 00:00:10,320
We learned in second grade

6
00:00:10,320 --> 00:00:12,080
Before JDK 21

7
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:14,190
Java only has platform threads

8
00:00:14,190 --> 00:00:15,470
so-called platform threads

9
00:00:15,470 --> 00:00:17,920
which means all scheduling rights of the threads

10
00:00:20,420 --> 00:00:22,420
The operating system employs time-sliced round-robin scheduling

11
00:00:22,420 --> 00:00:26,890
mechanisms such as multi-level queues to determine which thread executes

12
00:00:26,890 --> 00:00:29,450
This makes programmers feel

13
00:00:29,450 --> 00:00:32,470
The readily available resources of the operating system are virtually unlimited.

14
00:00:32,470 --> 00:00:34,230
So here lies the problem

15
00:00:34,230 --> 00:00:36,710
The scheduling of the operating system comes at a cost.

16
00:00:36,710 --> 00:00:39,370
the operating system kernel directly schedules

17
00:00:39,370 --> 00:00:43,200
causing thread switching to require entering kernel mode

18
00:00:43,200 --> 00:00:45,880
This involves a complete context switch in the system

19
00:00:45,880 --> 00:00:48,280
need to save and restore registers

20
00:00:48,280 --> 00:00:50,349
restore the context for scheduling decisions

21
00:00:50,349 --> 00:00:52,109
This overhead is relatively significant

22
00:00:52,109 --> 00:00:53,829
when the number of threads we create

23
00:00:53,829 --> 00:00:56,880
far exceeds the actual number of CPU cores

24
00:00:56,880 --> 00:01:00,820
the operating system aims to schedule these threads more fairly

25
00:01:00,820 --> 00:01:03,960
must frequently suspend and resume threads

26
00:01:03,960 --> 00:01:06,580
ensure that each task can progress normally

27
00:01:06,580 --> 00:01:09,300
Modern operating systems all employ preemptive scheduling

28
00:01:09,300 --> 00:01:12,020
The operating system can do so through interrupts

29
00:01:12,020 --> 00:01:14,919
preempt the context switch of the currently running CPU

30
00:01:14,919 --> 00:01:17,039
This switching is mandatory

31
00:01:17,039 --> 00:01:19,839
referred to as the preemptive multitasking mode

32
00:01:19,839 --> 00:01:22,580
Here we take a tomcat server as an example

33
00:01:22,580 --> 00:01:24,460
If the CPU has ten cores

34
00:01:24,460 --> 00:01:28,230
then this machine can only handle ten HTTP requests simultaneously

35
00:01:28,230 --> 00:01:29,970
This is clearly unacceptable

36
00:01:29,970 --> 00:01:32,270
but we found that this HTTP request

37
00:01:32,270 --> 00:01:35,140
most of the time is not spent on CPU computation

38
00:01:35,140 --> 00:01:36,620
this HTTP request

39
00:01:36,620 --> 00:01:38,900
may call third-party interfaces during processing

40
00:01:38,900 --> 00:01:41,400
or querying databases like REDIS

41
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:43,160
during the execution of these operations

42
00:01:43,160 --> 00:01:46,500
we naturally expect the operating system to suspend these threads

43
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:48,480
switch to other threads for execution

44
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:50,420
Of course, handling too many threads simultaneously

45
00:01:50,420 --> 00:01:54,150
the aforementioned CPU resources would still be exhausted

46
00:01:54,150 --> 00:01:56,750
Therefore, Tomcat sets a default value

47
00:01:56,750 --> 00:01:59,350
with a thread pool size of 200

48
00:01:59,350 --> 00:02:03,020
which means a maximum of 200 requests can be scheduled and processed simultaneously

49
00:02:03,020 --> 00:02:07,820
Specific parameters should be adjusted according to the CPU's load type and model

50
00:02:07,820 --> 00:02:08,560
make adjustments

51
00:02:08,560 --> 00:02:10,440
For example, if your configuration is excellent

52
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:14,320
or if the current service is purely a request forwarding service

53
00:02:14,320 --> 00:02:16,980
we can adjust this parameter higher

54
00:02:16,980 --> 00:02:19,320
Doesn't that sound very familiar

55
00:02:19,320 --> 00:02:19,900
Exactly

56
00:02:19,900 --> 00:02:23,300
This is the IO-intensive and CPU-intensive concept that our team often recites

57
00:02:23,300 --> 00:02:26,520
the configuration logic for intensive thread pool resources

58
00:02:26,520 --> 00:02:29,360
So the underlying meaning of so-called I/O-intensive

59
00:02:29,360 --> 00:02:31,810
This service doesn't use the CPU much.

60
00:02:31,810 --> 00:02:35,829
can frequently yield CPU resources to other threads

61
00:02:35,829 --> 00:02:39,529
If the thread pool's thread count limit is set too high

62
00:02:39,529 --> 00:02:42,929
can easily cause the operating system to frequently suspend

63
00:02:42,929 --> 00:02:44,649
resulting in degraded program performance

64
00:02:44,649 --> 00:02:45,989
set too low

65
00:02:45,989 --> 00:02:48,969
can also lead to a situation where threads are fully occupied

66
00:02:48,969 --> 00:02:51,309
the processor is still not running at full capacity

67
00:02:51,309 --> 00:02:52,519
resulting in waste

68
00:02:52,519 --> 00:02:55,519
So is there any way to solve this problem?

69
00:02:55,519 --> 00:02:56,979
Yes, my bro, yes

70
00:02:56,979 --> 00:02:59,160
That is Java's virtual threads

71
00:02:59,160 --> 00:03:02,100
The solution adopted by virtual threads is very simple

72
00:03:02,100 --> 00:03:04,900
Since the operating system's scheduling

73
00:03:04,900 --> 00:03:06,100
such a waste of time

74
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:08,930
Why don't we just move this scheduling to user space?

75
00:03:08,930 --> 00:03:11,270
JPM can schedule threads by itself

76
00:03:11,270 --> 00:03:14,570
In Java, the scheduling approach adopted for virtual threads

77
00:03:14,570 --> 00:03:16,780
called cooperative scheduling

78
00:03:16,780 --> 00:03:22,060
Cooperative scheduling means when a program experiences hang-ups or blocking

79
00:03:22,060 --> 00:03:23,910
such as the sleep function

80
00:03:23,910 --> 00:03:27,470
then the current CPU resources will be automatically allocated to

81
00:03:27,470 --> 00:03:29,560
another thread that needs to be executed

82
00:03:29,560 --> 00:03:33,260
Since such blocking is usually caused by IO waits

83
00:03:33,260 --> 00:03:36,200
Therefore, we need to frequently perform IO waits

84
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:38,240
while the CPU remains relatively idle

85
00:03:38,240 --> 00:03:40,000
In this Java code snippet

86
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:44,900
The program created more threads than the currently schedulable number of threads in the system

87
00:03:44,900 --> 00:03:46,390
one additional thread

88
00:03:46,390 --> 00:03:49,170
the extra thread in this case

89
00:03:49,170 --> 00:03:51,660
can still run normally

90
00:03:51,660 --> 00:03:53,780
When running the following code

91
00:03:53,780 --> 00:03:58,410
The program can still output the new virtual thread here

92
00:03:58,410 --> 00:04:01,610
This is because in the loop of other threads

93
00:04:01,610 --> 00:04:06,380
the sleep function will yield execution rights from other virtual threads

94
00:04:06,380 --> 00:04:08,750
yield to this new thread

95
00:04:08,910 --> 00:04:10,970
But if we make a slight change

96
00:04:10,970 --> 00:04:12,610
remove the sleep

97
00:04:12,610 --> 00:04:14,520
rerun this code

98
00:04:14,520 --> 00:04:18,240
we will find that the 'new v show si' part never gets printed

99
00:04:18,240 --> 00:04:21,260
This holds true for both JDK21 and JDK25.

100
00:04:21,260 --> 00:04:23,159
This is cooperative scheduling

101
00:04:23,159 --> 00:04:24,999
they need to negotiate with each other

102
00:04:24,999 --> 00:04:28,370
when to yield resources to other threads

103
00:04:28,370 --> 00:04:29,830
This scheduling mode

104
00:04:29,830 --> 00:04:33,410
The advantage is that it eliminates the need for the JVM to periodically interrupt operations

105
00:04:33,410 --> 00:04:35,930
because this would incur certain overhead

106
00:04:35,930 --> 00:04:39,770
The drawback is if you have 11 non-stop tasks

107
00:04:39,770 --> 00:04:43,930
which means 11 threads need to run on a 10-thread CPU

108
00:04:43,930 --> 00:04:47,890
then one of the tasks will continuously fail to be scheduled

109
00:04:47,890 --> 00:04:52,010
So what about the virtual threads in Go? We usually call them goroutines.

110
00:04:52,010 --> 00:04:55,050
It actually chose a different approach.

111
00:04:55,050 --> 00:05:00,380
We know that Go's threading is based on the GMP model.

112
00:05:00,380 --> 00:05:04,680
Similarly, Go also brings scheduling into the user-space program.

113
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:07,600
We usually refer to goroutines as coroutines

114
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:11,159
Here, the '协' primarily refers to cooperative.

115
00:05:11,159 --> 00:05:14,559
early versions of Go made choices similar to current Java

116
00:05:14,559 --> 00:05:16,859
is purely cooperatively scheduled

117
00:05:16,859 --> 00:05:18,430
which means

118
00:05:18,430 --> 00:05:24,520
If you run similar code in Go 1.13

119
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:27,560
the final result would be the same as in Java

120
00:05:27,560 --> 00:05:29,260
fails to output

121
00:05:29,260 --> 00:05:32,130
You might even get stuck with goroutines.

122
00:05:32,130 --> 00:05:36,350
but when running the same code in versions after 1.14G

123
00:05:36,350 --> 00:05:39,350
Goroutines can successfully output the results again

124
00:05:39,350 --> 00:05:40,830
Isn't it amazing?

125
00:05:40,830 --> 00:05:42,910
it's because the subsequent versions

126
00:05:42,910 --> 00:05:46,890
the Go language employs cooperative plus preemptive scheduling

127
00:05:46,890 --> 00:05:48,210
if a go routine

128
00:05:48,210 --> 00:05:51,250
running continuously on a logical processor for 10ms

129
00:05:51,250 --> 00:05:53,110
it will be marked as preemptible

130
00:05:53,110 --> 00:05:54,610
that is to say

131
00:05:54,610 --> 00:05:58,910
In higher versions of Go, there are two possibilities that can lead to context switching

132
00:05:58,910 --> 00:06:02,420
another is blocking or hanging

133
00:06:02,420 --> 00:06:06,659
the other is that it will be preempted by other coroutines if it runs for too long

134
00:06:06,659 --> 00:06:07,579
To summarize

135
00:06:07,579 --> 00:06:08,579
we can easily conclude

136
00:06:08,579 --> 00:06:10,700
The main advantage of virtual threads is

137
00:06:10,700 --> 00:06:13,700
The overhead of creating and destroying thread pools is very small

138
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:15,460
and are all user-mode operations

139
00:06:15,460 --> 00:06:16,980
Therefore, in most cases

140
00:06:16,980 --> 00:06:21,080
it needs to petrify virtual threads just like platform threads

141
00:06:21,080 --> 00:06:25,280
Therefore, we don't need to worry about specific thread pool parameter configurations

142
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:29,440
This was typically determined based on business attributes and stress testing in the past.

143
00:06:29,440 --> 00:06:32,270
determine the switching overhead of virtual threads

144
00:06:32,270 --> 00:06:34,110
is also a purely user-mode operation

145
00:06:34,110 --> 00:06:36,150
compared to system-level trapping

146
00:06:36,150 --> 00:06:37,950
can perform a thread switch

147
00:06:37,950 --> 00:06:41,230
Virtual threads in scenarios requiring frequent thread switching

148
00:06:41,230 --> 00:06:42,640
performance will be better

149
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:44,420
Now that we understand this principle,

